pouch boundary-line patch 0006 - AF_UNIX SOCK_STREAM over /srv byte mode

Phase 6 sub-chunk 12 (pouch-sockets). Maps musl's AF_UNIX SOCK_STREAM
surface onto Thylacine's /srv registry using the new BYTE-MODE
transport added to the kernel SrvConn at this sub-chunk. Twelve files,
one set of related changes.

  PAIRED WITH kernel changes (this commit, not in this patch file):
    kernel/include/thylacine/devsrv.h adds enum srv_mode {9P, BYTE}
      + SrvService.mode field. srv_reserve takes the mode.
    kernel/include/thylacine/srvconn.h adds SrvConn.byte_mode field
      + srvconn_set_byte_mode setter.
    kernel/include/thylacine/syscall.h adds SYS_POST_SERVICE_BYTE
      = 43, the byte-mode variant of SYS_POST_SERVICE = 26.
    kernel/devsrv.c::srv_conn_open_for_proc propagates the service
      mode onto every minted SrvConn BEFORE enqueuing it on the
      accept backlog.
    kernel/syscall.c::sys_srv_connect_for_proc SKIPS the 9P handshake
      when the SrvConn is byte-mode (a non-empty path is refused).
    kernel/syscall.c::sys_read/write_for_proc's KObj_SRV arm dispatches
      on cn->byte_mode: byte mode -> srvconn_client_send/recv (raw
      chan_produce/consume on c2s/s2c); 9P mode keeps the original
      srvconn_client_write/read path. The existing corvus + future
      stratumd consumers (SRV_MODE_9P, the default) are unaffected.

The translation table (POUCH-DESIGN.md section 6.2; revised at this
sub-chunk to acknowledge two transport modes):
  socket(AF_UNIX, SOCK_STREAM, 0)  pouch-side slot alloc; no kernel call
  bind(fd, /srv/<name>)            SYS_post_service_byte(<name>) -
                                   registers the service in BYTE mode
                                   (NOT the 9P mode corvus / stratumd
                                   use)
  listen(fd, backlog)              no-op (kernel registry has its own
                                   bounded accept queue)
  accept(fd)                       SYS_srv_accept(listener_h) returning
                                   a RAW kernel Spoor fd (not pouch-
                                   tagged; server-side I/O stays on
                                   the syscall-seam fast path)
  connect(fd, /srv/<name>)         SYS_srv_connect(<name>, NULL, 0) -
                                   the kernel reads the service mode
                                   and SKIPS the 9P handshake for
                                   byte mode, returning a SrvConn
                                   client handle ready for raw I/O
  getsockopt(SO_PEERCRED)          SYS_srv_peer(conn_h, &out) marshalled
                                   into a struct ucred (peer stripes
                                   -> ucred.pid; uid/gid are 0 at
                                   v1.0 since Thylacine has no uid
                                   model)
  read / write / close             dispatch through pouch_sock_kernel_fd
                                   (a single bit test on the common
                                   path), routing tagged fds to their
                                   slot's stored kernel handle

  arch/aarch64/bits/syscall.h.in   Adds five Thylacine /srv extension
      numbers - __NR_post_service 26, __NR_srv_accept 27, __NR_srv_peer
      28, __NR_srv_connect 30, __NR_post_service_byte 43 - so musl's
      sed pass generates the SYS_post_service / SYS_srv_accept /
      SYS_srv_peer / SYS_srv_connect / SYS_post_service_byte aliases
      the replacement socket files reference.

  src/internal/_pouch_socket.h     New header. The slot-table API +
      tag-bit encoding (POUCH_SOCK_TAG = 0x40000000; sits above the
      kernel's PROC_HANDLE_MAX so no real kernel fd ever overlaps a
      pouch socket fd). POUCH_SOCK_MAX = 8 (generous for v1.0 servers;
      per-Proc concurrent /srv client cap remains 1).

  src/network/_pouch_socket.c      New file. The slot table + the
      three core helpers (pouch_sock_alloc, pouch_sock_kernel_fd,
      pouch_sock_close). All structural changes happen under a single
      LOCK / UNLOCK pair around the static table. pthread peers share
      the table; serialization is sufficient because the table
      operations are short (O(POUCH_SOCK_MAX) at worst) and contention
      is rare (sockets aren't accept-heavy at v1.0).

  src/network/socket.c             Full rewrite. AF_UNIX SOCK_STREAM
      only; AF_INET / SOCK_DGRAM / etc return EAFNOSUPPORT /
      EPROTONOSUPPORT per invariant P-3 (no silently-wrong POSIX).
      SOCK_CLOEXEC / SOCK_NONBLOCK accepted, silently no-op at v1.0.

  src/network/bind.c               Full rewrite. Extracts the service
      name from sun_path - "/srv/<name>" or relative "<name>" - and
      calls SYS_post_service_byte (not SYS_post_service - pouch
      sockets are byte-mode services; the 9P-mode variant is reserved
      for corvus and stratumd). The kernel post-gate
      (PROC_FLAG_MAY_POST_SERVICE) must already be stamped on the
      calling Proc; joey grants it at spawn via t_spawn_with_perms.

  src/network/listen.c             Full rewrite. No-op at v1.0.

  src/network/accept.c             Full rewrite. SYS_srv_accept on
      the slot's listener handle; returns the kernel-minted Spoor fd
      DIRECTLY (NOT pouch-tagged). Server-side I/O bypasses the
      pouch dispatch shim.

  src/network/accept4.c            Full rewrite. Delegates to accept()
      after flag validation. SOCK_CLOEXEC / SOCK_NONBLOCK no-op;
      unrecognized flags get EINVAL.

  src/network/connect.c            Full rewrite. Same sun_path -> name
      extraction as bind. Calls SYS_srv_connect with path_len == 0
      (the kernel's "no Twalk" case - which the byte-mode kernel
      handler now uses to also skip the 9P handshake entirely).
      Per-Proc concurrent client cap = 1 - a second connect() before
      closing the first gets ECONNREFUSED.

  src/network/getsockopt.c         Full rewrite. SOL_SOCKET +
      SO_PEERCRED -> SYS_srv_peer -> ucred marshal. All other levels
      and options return ENOPROTOOPT at v1.0.

  src/unistd/read.c                Patched. Single-bit tag check;
      tagged fd dispatches through pouch_sock_kernel_fd to the slot's
      stored kernel handle; untagged passes straight to SYS_read.
      The cancellable path (syscall_cp) is preserved on both arms.

  src/unistd/write.c               Patched. Same shape as read.c.

  src/unistd/close.c               Patched. Tagged fd routes through
      pouch_sock_close (frees slot + closes kernel handle if any);
      untagged falls through to the pristine __aio_close +
      __syscall_cp(SYS_close) path.

Binding design: docs/POUCH-DESIGN.md sub-chunk 12 (section 14),
section 6.2 (revised to include the byte-mode transport). Invariants
P-1, P-3, P-4. Reference: docs/reference/78-pouch.md ("The AF_UNIX
SOCK_STREAM backend" + "The byte-mode SrvConn").

Proving binary: /pouch-hello-sockets - end-to-end AF_UNIX SOCK_STREAM
round trip via the byte-mode /srv. Two pthreads in one Proc do the
full bind / listen / accept / connect / read / write / SO_PEERCRED /
close dance.
